{{Infobox person |name = Minnie A. Cumnock Blodgett |image = |image_size = |caption = |birth_name = Minnie Alice Cumnock |birth_date = 1862 |birth_place = [[Lowell, Massachusetts]] |death_date = {{Death date and age|1931|10|13|1862|11}} |death_place = |residence = [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]] |citizenship = |nationality = [[United States|American]] |occupation = Public Health, Philanthropy |spouse = [[John W. Blodgett]] married 1895 until her death 1931 |parents={{Plainlist| * Delos A. Blodgett * Jennie S. Wood }} |children ={{Plainlist| * John Wood Blodgett, Jr. (1901 - 1987) * Kathrine Cumnock Blodgett Hadley ({{Birth date|1898|01|13}} - {{Death date and age|1980|08|11|1898|01|13}}) }} |alma_mater = {{Plainlist| * [[Vassar College]] (1884) }} |doctoral_advisor = |doctoral_students = |known_for = |influences = |influenced = |prizes = |signature = |signature_size = }} {{Infobox NRHP | name = John W. Blodgett Estate | nrhp_type = | designated_other1_name = Michigan State Historic Site | designated_other1_abbr = MSHS | designated_other1_link = Michigan State Historic Preservation Office | designated_other1_date = December 8, 1977<ref name=MCGI>{{cite web|publisher=State of Michigan |url=http://www.mcgi.state.mi.us/hso/sites/7858.htm |title=John W. and Minnie Cummock Blodgett Estate |accessdate=March 6, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528153203/http://www.mcgi.state.mi.us/hso/sites/7858.htm |archivedate=May 28, 2012 |df= }}</ref> | designated_other1_color = CornflowerBlue | designated_other1_number = P23712 | designated_other1_num_position = bottom | image = Landmarks_053.JPG | alt = | caption = | map_alt = | map_caption = | coordinates = {{coord|42|57|26|N|85|37|25|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = Michigan | location = [[East Grand Rapids, Michigan]] | area = {{convert|8|acre|ha}} | built = 1928 | architect = Walker and Gillette | architecture = [[Colonial Revival]] | added = {{dts|1983|7|28}} | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | refnum = 83000877<ref name=NRIS>{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref> | mpsub = | governing_body = }} '''Minnie Cumnock Blodgett''' (1862&ndash;1931) graduated from [[Vassar College]] in 1884, later becoming a trustee (1917&ndash;1931). She is the mother of Katharine Blodgett Hadley (VC '20), who was also a Vassar trustee (1942&ndash;1954), and was chairman of the Board (1945&ndash;1952).<ref name="VassarChronicle2">{{cite web |url= http://chronology.vassar.edu/records/1928/1928-blodgett.html |title= The Minnie Cumnock Blodgett Hall of Euthenics was completed, York & Sawyer, architects. - - A Documentary Chronicle of Vassar College |author= Vassar Historian |date= |website= chronology.vassar.edu/ |publisher= |accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref>
Her husband, [[John W. Blodgett]], built their estate, which they named [[John W. Blodgett Estate|Brookby]], where they made their Grand Rapids home.
==Vassar College and Euthenics program== After [[Ellen Swallow Richards]]' death in 1911, [[Julia Lathrop]] (1858&ndash;1932), another of Vassar's most distinguished alumnae, continued to promote the development of an interdisciplinary program in [[euthenics]] at the college. Lathrop soon teamed with alumna Minnie Cumnock Blodgett, who with her husband, John Wood Blodgett, offered financial support to create a program of euthenics at [[Vassar College]]. Curriculum planning, suggested by Vassar President [[Henry Noble MacCracken]] in 1922, began in earnest by 1923.<ref name="VassarEuthenicsHistory">{{cite web|url=http://vcencyclopedia.vassar.edu/three-chapters/the-disappointing-first-thrust-of-euthenics.html |title=The Disappointing First Thrust of Euthenics |author=Vassar Historian |date= |website=vcencyclopedia.vassar.edu |publisher= |accessdate=26 August 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140127020842/http://vcencyclopedia.vassar.edu/three-chapters/the-disappointing-first-thrust-of-euthenics.html |archivedate=27 January 2014 |df= }}</ref>
In 1925, through a gift of $550,000.00 from Mrs. Blodgett, the Institute of Euthenics was founded at Vassar. Its aim was "to supply scientific knowledge of the complex problems of adjustment between individuals and the environment, emphasizing home and family."<ref name="NYTimesObituary">{{cite web |url= http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F20D1EFC395F177A93C6A8178BD95F458385F9 |title= SOCIAL WORKER DIES AT 68 ON VISIT HERE - Mrs. John W. Blodgett of Grand Rapids Had Been Guest of Her Daughter and Son-in-Law. ONCE TRUSTEE OF VASSAR Director of Child Study Association and of National Organization for Public Health Nursing. |author= |year= 1931 |website= nytimes.com |publisher= NY Times |accessdate=5 September 2013}}</ref> Vassar historian Colton Johnson noted "The Blodgetts' gift was the largest gift given to the College after Matthew Vassar donated $408,000 in 1861 to get the College started ... Their intention was to bring into the curriculum of the College a course of study specifically designed around the ideas of Ellen Swallow Richards."
==Death== Mrs. John Wood Blodgett died suddenly of heart disease on October 13, 1931 in her suite in [[The St. Regis Hotel]], New York, NY. She was there to attend meetings for two health organizations and spend some time visiting her daughter and son-in-law. According to her obituary in the ''New York Times'', she was a director of the Child Study Association, the National Organization for Public Health Nursing, and was a member of the National Committee on Mental Hygiene. She was the daughter of the late Mr. and Mrs. Alexander G. Cunnock [sic] of Lowell, Mass. She was also president of the D.A. Blodgett Home for Children, and sat on the board of trustees at Vassar College.<ref name="NYTimesObituary" />
==Descendants== Descendants include: * John Wood Blodgett, Jr., who married Sally Reed Gallagher, of Milton, MA, on September 28, 1939. He attended St. Mark's School in Southboro, and graduated Harvard in 1923.<ref name="NYTimesWedding2">{{cite web |url= http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0B1EFE3B54107A93CAA81782D85F4D8385F9 |title= SALLY R. GALLAGHER TO MARRY SEPT. 28; Sister to Be Maid of Honor for Fiancee of J.W. Blodgett Jr. |author= NY Times |year= 1939 |website= nytimes.com |publisher= NY Times |accessdate=5 September 2013}}</ref> * Kathrine Cumnock Blodgett Hadley, who married Major Morris Hadley, July 12, 1919.<ref name="NYTimesWedding">{{cite web |url= https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F30F1FFC395B11728DDDAA0994DF405B898DF1D3 |title= MISS BLODGETT WED TO MORRIS HADLEY; Bride of Son of Yale's President at Her Summer Home at Prides Crossing, Mass. |author= NY Times |year= 1919 |website= nytimes.com |publisher= NY Times |accessdate=5 September 2013}}</ref> * John Wood Blodgett Hadley (1930 - 1994).<ref name="NYTimesObituary2">{{cite web |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1994/11/10/obituaries/john-hadley-64-philanthropist-and-investor.html |title= John [Wood Blodgett] Hadley, 64, Philanthropist And Investor |author= WOLFGANG SAXON |year= 1996 |website= nytimes.com |publisher= NY Times Obituary |accessdate=5 September 2013}}</ref> who married Katrina Boyden Hadley (1930-1969), she is buried in the Blodgett Plot.
